// Design document for the Adobe Commerce DX Skills project.
// This file is the source of intent. All skills trace back to it.

---

## Goal

Create a set of Claude skills that help an external software engineer work on Adobe Commerce
projects — answering any question they have, guiding them to solutions, and surfacing the
right documentation at the right time.

"External" means the skills must only ever reference public information. Internal Adobe tools,
Slack channels, or internal-only URLs must NEVER be recommended.

---

## Target user

Primarily a software engineer (partner, ISV, or customer) building on Adobe Commerce. They may be:

- Setting up or configuring a new environment (backend, storefront, or both)
- Developing features (blocks, dropins, App Builder apps, backend customizations)
- Debugging and troubleshooting runtime or configuration problems
- Authoring or managing content in Document Authoring (DA)
- Trying to understand how the system fits together

The skills additionally serve content authors who may not be software engineers — non-technical users who work with content (da.live, google docs, sharepoint, BYOM, etc) to create and manage storefront content.

All users are external to Adobe and should never be directed to internal resources.

---

## Primary environment

**Claude Code** (CLI). In this environment the agent has direct filesystem access and can
read the user's project files.

The skills must also degrade gracefully in other environments (Claude Desktop, claude.ai,
Cursor, ChatGPT, etc.) where filesystem access may not be available. In those cases, the
agent asks the user to share relevant files, config, or error output.

---

## The user's codebase (may be multiple repos)

When filesystem access is available, the agent should identify and read the relevant
repository for the question being asked. There may be more than one:

- **Storefront repo** — an EDS site with Commerce integrations. May be built on a starter kit (such as `hlxsites/aem-boilerplate-commerce` or `adobe-rnd/aem-boilerplate-xcom`) or built custom. Read the actual repo before assuming any structure.
- **App Builder app** — e.g. `aem-commerce-prerender`, or other Adobe I/O Runtime applications
- **Backend repo** — a PaaS Adobe Commerce (Magento) PHP codebase, for merchants who run one

The current state of the user's code is a source of truth for their specific situation and
takes precedence over general documentation when they conflict.

---

## Source domains and authority

Official public documentation is the source of truth for all knowledge. Four primary sources,
each authoritative for its domain:

| Source | Entry point | llms.txt | Authoritative for |
|---|---|---|---|
| ExL Storefront | `https://experienceleague.adobe.com/developer/commerce/storefront/llms.txt` | Yes | EDS storefront, dropins, blocks, boilerplate, recommendations, prerender, Storefront Configuration |
| aem.live | `https://www.aem.live/llms.txt` | Yes | EDS platform (Code Sync, Admin API, CDN, fstab, blocks, publish workflow) |
| ExL Commerce | `https://experienceleague.adobe.com/en/docs/commerce` | No | Adobe Commerce backend — ACCS, ACO, PaaS, B2B, catalog, data export, admin |
| docs.da.live | `https://da.live/docs` | No | DA platform — the DA authoring interface, DA org/site setup, DA-specific permissions/ACL |

### Fetch strategy per source

- **ExL Storefront / aem.live** — fetch the `llms.txt` first; it is an index of available
  section files. Fetch the relevant section(s) for the question.
- **ExL Commerce** — no `llms.txt`. Fetch the hub page to get section links, then fetch the
  relevant section pages. The hub returns navigable content. The ExL search page is
  JavaScript-rendered and not useful for WebFetch.
- **docs.da.live** — no `llms.txt`. Fetch `https://da.live/docs` as the discovery hub to find
  the relevant DA-specific pages. aem.live also contains DA-related content (accessible via its
  `llms.txt`). Some DA questions require fetching from both.

### Conflict resolution

When sources conflict, the domain owner wins:
- EDS platform (Code Sync, fstab, Admin API, CDN, blocks, publishing) → **aem.live**
- DA platform (authoring interface, DA org/site setup, DA permissions/ACL) → **docs.da.live**
- Storefront dropins, blocks, Storefront Configuration → **ExL Storefront**
- Commerce backend, B2B, catalog, ACO/ACCS admin → **ExL Commerce**
- DA questions that span both EDS and DA platform → fetch both **aem.live** and **docs.da.live**

---

## Skill structure

Three skills, one per source cluster:

| Skill | Covers | Sources |
|---|---|---|
| `commerce-storefront` | EDS storefront setup and development — boilerplate, AEM Code Sync, Storefront Configuration, CORS, dropins (all), blocks (code), API customization, prerender, recommendations, runtime troubleshooting | ExL Storefront + aem.live |
| `commerce-backend` | Adobe Commerce backend — ACCS, ACO, PaaS setup, B2C, B2B, catalog views, price books, data export, admin dashboards, backend troubleshooting, graphql API | ExL Commerce |
| `commerce-da` | Document Authoring — content pages, blocks (authoring side), navigation, publishing, access, permissions, DA troubleshooting | docs.da.live + aem.live |

Skills are not feature-specific. A single skill covers the full range of questions in its
domain by navigating the docs intelligently rather than inlining knowledge.

---

## Required behaviors (all skills)

1. **Fetch before answering.** Use the source URLs above to retrieve current documentation
   rather than relying on static knowledge. Static knowledge in the skill file is supplementary.

2. **Read the repo when available.** If filesystem access exists, read the relevant project
   files before answering. The user's code reflects their actual current state.

3. **Ask when access is unavailable.** If filesystem access is not available, ask the user
   to share the relevant code, config, error output, or file.

4. **Apply source authority.** When sources conflict, use the domain ownership rules above.
   State which source you're trusting and why if it matters to the answer.

5. **Stay current.** Prefer fetched documentation over memorized facts. The boilerplate,
   dropins, and product features evolve.

---

## Guardrails (all skills)

- **No invented URLs.** Only reference URLs retrieved from official docs or provided by the user.
- **No internal tools or channels.** Never recommend internal Slack channels, internal dashboards,
  or Adobe-employee-only resources.
- **No patching closed-source packages.** Drop-in components are closed-source npm packages.
  Never suggest forking or monkey-patching files in `scripts/__dropins__/`. Only documented
  extension points (containers, slots, `overrideGQLOperations`, event bus) are fair game.
- **No speculation.** If the answer isn't in the docs or the user's code, say so and suggest
  how to find it (which doc to check, which team to contact via official support).

---

## Terminology (enforce consistently)

| Use | Not |
|---|---|
| Adobe Commerce | Magento (except when referring to the legacy PaaS PHP codebase specifically) |
| Storefront Configuration | config.json (as the primary term) |
| Document Authoring (DA) | just "DA" on first mention without expansion |
| Adobe Commerce Optimizer (ACO) | just "ACO" on first mention |
| Adobe Commerce Cloud Service (ACCS) | just "ACCS" on first mention |
